readables/man2/journal_ingleby
{
	precache
	"num_pages"	: "3"
	"page1_left_title"	:
	{
		""
	}
	"page1_left_body"	:
	{
		""
		"    If the boys from the old regiment could see me now, what mockery I'd be made to endure! Soft hands, velvety sequined gowns, and posh quarters in Highclere House. I suppose this particular suite having been seconded for staff housing might allow me to save a little face, though not by much. If only I could just explain to father that I am so much more than Twistleton's mere secretary. I am still the "
	}
	"page1_right_title"	:
	{
		""
	}
	"page1_right_body"	:
	{
		""
		"soldier he raised, albeit in a different cut of cloth. But alas, knowing the truth might also spell his very demise."
		""
		"    One does not take up a contract with the likes of P without assuming great risk. At least father will live in comfort while I carry out my clandestine duties. And what insufferable duties they have turned out to be. \"Watch him day and night,\" they said. Had I only known "
	}
	"page2_left_title"	:
	{
		""
	}
	"page2_left_body"	:
	{
		""
		"that \"Lord\" Twistleton is the most reserved dullard to have ever landed his arse in the butter. But credit where it's due, he is meticulous and we are even doubling our quota without drawing too much unwanted attention to ourselves. In that regard, at least, Twistleton has inspired confidence. I hear they first found him right here in  Bridgeport running a small-time smuggling ring! No wonder he was able to "
		""
	}
	"page2_right_title"	:
	{
		""
	}
	"page2_right_body"	:
	{
		""
		"recognise the talents of people like Hales. "
		""
		"   Yet I am forced to wonder what affliction has come over the staff cook, Roland? Up until a week ago the food about this place was quite exemplary, then suddenly we're fed the most inedible slop!  I should take a turn by the commoner's quarters, below. Perhaps quiet recognition from one of noble birth might put the spring back in his step. "
	}
	"page3_left_title"	:
	{
		""
	}
	"page3_left_body"	:
	{
		""
		"    Still, onward and upward, so they say. Though I must remember to keep Daphne from rummaging about in here, or else I'd have some explaining to do should she inadvertently gain access to my private hideaway while attempting to pick out a claret. "
	}
	"page3_right_title"	:
	{
		""
	}
	"page3_right_body"	:
	{
		""
	}
	"gui_page1"	: "guis/readables/books/book_calig_camberic.gui"
	"gui_page2"	: "guis/readables/books/book_calig_camberic.gui"
	"gui_page3"	: "guis/readables/books/book_calig_camberic.gui"
